  1. Create a scatter plot of the Percent Under $25K vs rate.
ggplot(data = prison) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = pct_under_25K , y = rate))
  1. Use aesthetics to indicate cost
ggplot(data = prison) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = pct_under_25K , y = rate, color = cost))

ggplot(data = prison) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = pct_under_25K , y = rate, color = cost), size = 12, shape = 20)

Which variables in the chetty data frame are appropriate x variables for a bar graph?

  • Any categorical variable can be the x-variable in a bar graph, so cz_name, state, region, division, and urban.
  • Note that the variables with values of either 0 or 1 (top_100, inctax_progressive, eitc) are theoretically categorical because there are only two options for the value. However, in this data frame they are read in as âdblâ which is a continuous numerical variable type. Because I converted top_100 to a âfactor,â it is also categorical, and you could do the same with the other 0/1 variables. Weâll learn more about this later!
  1. Make two separate bar graphs for two different x variables.
#first plot
ggplot(data=chetty, mapping=aes(x=region)) +
  geom_bar()
#second plot
ggplot(data=chetty, mapping=aes(x=state)) +
  geom_bar()
  1. Make two more bar graphs that display proportions rather than counts of your selected variables.
ggplot(data=chetty, mapping=aes(x=state, y = stat(prop), group = 1)) +
  geom_bar()
